"Too bad!" muttered Chet. "Can't beat \i that \i0 boat."\par
"Just wait and see," advised Frank.\par
The changing breeze filled the sail and again the ice-boat sprang forward. The other craft was slowing down, and the steersman was des' perately trying to bring it about with the wind again. But he was too late. The Hardy boys' boat swept triumphantly across his bow and Chet gave a shout of delight. On down the bay sped the little craft and by the time the other boat's sails were billowing again the lads were far in the lead. Looking back, they saw the beaten rival slowly turning about into the wind, heading back up the bay.\par
"That's real seamanship!" declared Joe.\par
"Oh, well, we have a good boat," returned Prank, refusing to claim any credit for the victory. "We were lucky the wind changed."\par
Ahead of them loomed a high, gloomy cliff, rising sheer from the ice. Beyond that, they knew, was one of the largest coves on Barmet Bay, known as Cabin Cove.\par
"Let's go on and take a look at Cabin Island," suggested Chet. "Seeing we're so dose to the place we might as well pay it a visit."\par
"Sure thing," approved the others.\par
Cabin Island, in Cabin Cove, was a lonely spot, even more desolate now that the bay was\par
